5|$|When questioned, Patrick Darby {{testified that}} in 1824, Beauchamp had {{solicited}} his services in order <b>to</b> <b>bring</b> <b>suit</b> against Sharp for unspecified charges. During their ensuing conversations, Beauchamp had related {{the story of}} Sharp's abandonment of Anna Cooke and her child, swearing that he would kill him one day, {{even if he had}} to come to Frankfort and shoot him down in the street. The combined testimonies of Eliza Sharp and Patrick Darby were sufficient to persuade the city magistrates to hold Beauchamp for trial during the circuit court's next term, which began in March 1826.|$|E
